      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get the dice thing but it still sounds kinda impossible. you said it's like they're communicating faster than light. how do scientists actually explain that part? like is there some hidden mechanism that makes it \"spooky\" like einstein said?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, Einstein did indeed call it \"spooky action at a distance,\" and he was puzzled by the idea that particles could be connected in such a way that they seemed to communicate instantaneously, faster than the speed of light. Einstein, along with many other physicists, found this concept difficult to accept because it seemed to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than light.\n\nHowever, scientists have developed theories and experiments to explain this phenomenon without invoking any hidden mechanisms or faster-than-light communication. One of the key ideas is that entangled particles are not communicating in the traditional sense. Instead, their properties are intertwined from the moment they are created, and when you measure one particle, you instantly know the state of the other, even if they are far apart.\n\nThis doesn't mean that information is being sent between the particles faster than light. In fact, it's impossible to use this phenomenon to send information faster than light, because the outcome of the measurement is random. You can't control what the other particle will show, so you can't use it to send a message.\n\nSo, while it may seem \"spooky\" or impossible, quantum entanglement is a well-established phenomenon that has been confirmed by numerous experiments. It's a fundamental aspect of the quantum",
      "source": "target",
